<!-- FAQ -->
<section class="cat-page-faq">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="cat-page-faq-head">
      <span class="eyebrow">Frequently asked questions</span>
      <h2>What people ask us most about IPL.</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="cat-page-faq-list">
      <div class="cat-page-faq-item open">
        <button class="cat-page-faq-q" type="button">How many sessions will I need? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="cat-page-faq-a"><p>Between 6 and 10 sessions, spaced according to the area and hair growth cycle. Face and underarms: every 4-6 weeks. Legs and body: every 6-8 weeks. A one-off top-up once a year after completing the plan.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="cat-page-faq-item">
        <button class="cat-page-faq-q" type="button">Does it hurt? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="cat-page-faq-a"><p>A brief snapping sensation with each light pulse. Far more comfortable than hot wax or diode laser. Most people don't need any anaesthetic.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="cat-page-faq-item">
        <button class="cat-page-faq-q" type="button">Can I have IPL in summer? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="cat-page-faq-a"><p>Ideally IPL is done outside periods of intense sun exposure. Summer is fine if your skin isn't tanned and you use strict sunscreen. For tanned skin it's better to wait until autumn or winter.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="cat-page-faq-item">
        <button class="cat-page-faq-q" type="button">What about pregnancy or breastfeeding? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="cat-page-faq-a"><p>IPL isn't validated for pregnancy or breastfeeding as a precaution, even though there is no evidence of harm. We wait until breastfeeding ends before starting a plan.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="cat-page-faq-item">
        <button class="cat-page-faq-q" type="button">IPL vs diode laser? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="cat-page-faq-a"><p>Both reduce hair permanently. IPL uses broad-spectrum pulsed light (more flexible across different areas and skin types). Diode laser uses a single coherent wavelength (more effective on very dark hair and fair skin, but less versatile).</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

